1106,IssuesEvent,2015-09-06 17:17:54+00:00,6865808,danilop/yas3fs,1550395,danilop,,,closed,Add option to use AWS Signature Version 4/support for new AWS locations,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/danilop/yas3fs/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],3,"Newer AWS locations (in my case Frankfurt) will only authenticate clients that use AWS Signature Version 4. It would be nice to have it as an option, because these newer locations are unusable otherwise. SigV4 seems to require an explicit S3 host parameter so this would have to be added as a command line option, too. My suggestion is to introduce a `--s3-host` flag. If set, SigV4 should automatically be used. Alternatively a new `--s3-sigv4` flag could be used to make this more explicit.

It seems that older locations all support SigV4 so it should not be a problem to be compatible with those. Maybe users of these older locations will benefit from SigV4 as well as it promises to provide increased security and performance, but I didn't research that any further. I am just trying to get this to work with an S3 bucket in Frankfurt.

Apparently, enabling SigV4 with boto requires two changes. First, you need to set `os.environ['S3_USE_SIGV4'] = 'True`. Second, you need to set the host parameter when calling `S3Connection()`, or `boto.connect_s3()`, respectively. Also see https://github.com/boto/boto/issues/2741

I'm a complete Python noob so I may not be the most suitable person to make a PR for this, but I can give it a try if no one else has the time.",{},{}
1121,IssuesEvent,2017-12-21 08:11:24+00:00,16331291,davisking/dlib,11925522,RovingBit,,,reopened,"""hinge loss"" in in ""loss_metric"" compare to ""standard/general hinge loss""",[],[],4,"Standard/General hinge loss:
loss = MAX(0, L(P, P+) - L(P, P-)  + C)

Hinge loss in dlib's loss_metric implementation:
loss(postive) = MAX(0, L(P, P+) - dist_thresh + C)
loss(negtive) = MAX(0, dist_thresh - L(P, P-)  + C)
loss = loss(postive) + loss(negtive)

It seems that all ""sphere's radius"" in dlib's impl have the same ""radius < dist_thresh"" but the standard hinge loss.

I want to train a network to compare images similarity, both in the same label(johns) and in different labels(john/david/tom...).

In the same label(john1.jpg compare to johnx.jpg):
I think dlib's ""hinge loss"" implementation will perform better

But how it is performed in different labels(johnx.jpg compare to tomx.jpg):
Which one is better in theory?
Dose dlib's impl of ""hinge loss"" is a optimized one?
What's the differences?

my english is bad, sorry.
thank you and for your great dlib!

best regards.
",{},{}
1139,IssuesEvent,2015-09-14 13:37:24+00:00,16331291,davisking/dlib,385379,severin-lemaignan,,,opened,Use function multi-versioning (on supported platforms) to ensure optimized code whenever possible,[],[],0,"``gcc-4.8`` introduced the concept of [function multiversioning](https://gcc.gnu.org/wiki/FunctionMultiVersioning) to ease support of SSE/AVX (or any other ISA specific optimization) be providing automatic runtime enabling of optimized code when supported by the CPU.

While this would introduce ``gcc`` specific code into ``dlib``, it would ensure that optimized code is always used (on platforms supporting ``gcc``) when supported by the host CPU.",{},{}
