1519,IssuesEvent,2015-07-29 15:11:30+00:00,19155959,dagraham/etm-tk,3173673,therden,,,opened,Problems with editing recurring tasks,[],[],0,"**Scenario:**  editing either ""This instance"" or ""This and all subsequent instances"" of a recurring task which has prior @f and/or **@-** datetime values.

*Problem 1:*
While ETM discards datetime values associated with **@-** which precede ""this instance"", it then leaves that key in the item *even if no associated datetime values remain*.  Consequently, when the user tries to write/save their item, ETM then interprets the ""**@-** [no datetime value]"" as a reference to 12:00am on the current day and (unless that particular datetime value is generated by the repetition rule) produces an error message. 

*Fix 1:*  ETM should remove all **@-** datetime values which don't match the auto-edited recurring rule which it creates for ""this"" or ""this and future"" instances, and if no **@-** values remain then it should likewise remove the **@-** key.

*Problem 2:*
Unlike it's handling of @- datetime values, ETM does *not* discard @f datetime values which pre-date ""this instance"".  If the user doesn't manually remove them, when she tries to write/save the item ETM produces an error message.

*Fix 2:*  when ETM creates the new item representing ""this instance"" or ""this and all subsequent instances"", it should remove all @f datetime values which don't match the auto-edited recurring rule it creates, and if no @f values remain then it should likewise remove the @f key.
",{},{}
1534,IssuesEvent,2016-10-14 20:25:53+00:00,10155460,dbader/schedule,1958116,msoedov,,,opened,Add api to start scheduler in a separate Thread ,[],[],0,"I've noticed common pattern across my services with `schedule` where I use the following block
```python
while True:
    schedule.run_pending()
    time.sleep(1)
```

as

```python

....
def spawn():
    while True:
        schedule.run_pending()
        time.sleep(1)

if __name__ == '__main__':
   Thread(target=spawn).start()
   ....
```
to schedule some tasks but continue running code in the main thread. I think will be really useful to  have `spawn` method in the library",{},{}
1551,IssuesEvent,2017-12-25 20:12:49+00:00,77148264,deeplook/svglib,1001778,deeplook,,,opened,Investigate implicit line operators in <path>,[],[],0,"I've stumbled over a very simply logo that svglib does partly not render (the blueish triangle is missing): https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c7/HERE_logo.svg. I does appear though when adding `l` operators to the first path, turning it into: 

```xml
<path d=""m 26.95,66.453001 l -11,11 l -11,-11 l 22,0 z"" style=""fill:#65c1c2"" />
``` 
So there seems to be some convention about implicit `l` operators that is not followed by svglib, yet. This is simply a ticket to investigate this further.",{},{}
