2172,IssuesEvent,2017-12-01 04:29:40+00:00,108187130,mhammond/pywin32,1095373,leandor,,,opened,Provide a way to obtain the original IUnknown pointer out of the containing python object,[],[],0,"Hey there,

I was trying to make python work with a COM library of my own... and I got to a showstopper when I found that I can return back to the library a object (which is a pure IUnknown) that I receive from it.

The use case is something like this:

```idl
    HRESULT _stdcall Enumerate(
              [in, out]
              IUnknown** Enum,
              [out]
              <some type here>* Item,
              [out, retval]
              VARIANT_BOOL* Return
            );
```
That method returns as out an object (Enum) that maintains the context for the enumeration, and is assumed to be opaque to the user... so he need to pass them back the same value he received originally.

When I try to call this method from Python, the Enum value comes out as an instance of PyIUnknown, which contains the actual pointer object that I need... but I haven't found any way to get that value out of it.

This is the python syntax I'm using to call the above method... and it works, for one iteration, until I need to call it back with the value of enum I received the first time.
```python
prev = None
item = None
ok = True

while ok:
    ok, enum, item = results.Enumerate(prev)
    # does something with item here... and that part actually works!
    prev = enum.<I need something here I can use to get the actual IUnknown>
```
",{},{}
