3256,IssuesEvent,2016-04-15 11:12:56+00:00,8292338,ultrabug/py3status,474389,ultrabug,,,reopened,Support for format_time in tztime module,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ultrabug/py3status/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}]",[],3,"The tztime module from i3status introduced another ```format_time``` option to enable pango markup: https://i3wm.org/i3status/manpage.html#_tztime

As py3status handles the tztime module, this new option needs to be taken into account when parsing the time's format. Currently, when using ```format_time```, the time stops updating and adds the ```%Y,%m,%d``` formatstrings to the time (see [here](https://github.com/ultrabug/py3status/blob/master/py3status/__init__.py#L413)).",{},{}
3262,IssuesEvent,2018-01-21 17:58:53+00:00,8292338,ultrabug/py3status,852504,lasers,,,opened,Recognizing on_click limitations,[],[],0,"I address a thing or two about `on_click` limitations that I notice sometimes with few modules such as `spotify` recently, `transmission` and maybe `external_script`. This could apply to `getjson` and future modules in some scenarios.

# ISSUE 1
```
# this works.... but oh shit... how can i break this up?
spotify
{
    on_click 1 = 'exec dbus-send --print-reply --dest=org.mpris.MediaPlayer2.spotify /org/mpris/MediaPlayer2 org.mpris.MediaPlayer2.Player.PlayPause ; exec py3-cmd update spotify'
}
```
```
# does not work... fail. :\
spotify {
    cmd = 'exec dbus-send --print-reply --dest=org.mpris.MediaPlayer2.spotify '
    cmd += '/org/mpris/MediaPlayer2 org.mpris.MediaPlayer2.Player.PlayPause '
    cmd += '; exec py3-cmd update spotify'

    on_click 1 = cmd   
}
```

# ISSUE 2
I chained `self.py3-cmd update spotify` above because I need some delay after the click for better user experience with `spotify` via `on_click`. I was just trying things and the command above does not work anyway. I get some points for trying?

The solution is to do this inside the `spotify` module with `sleep()`... but for `on_click`, the solution is to use this patch. This patch is bad for other modules like `backlight`, `volume_status`, `xrandr_lmao`, `hueshift`, etc.
```
diff --git a/py3status/events.py b/py3status/events.py
index 2b658b4d..3c9b2e96 100644
--- a/py3status/events.py
+++ b/py3status/events.py
@@ -1,5 +1,6 @@
 import select
 import sys
+import time
 
 from threading import Thread
 from subprocess import Popen, PIPE
@@ -135,6 +136,12 @@ class Events(Thread):
             self.i3_msg(module_name, command)
             # to make the bar more responsive to users we ask for a refresh
             # of the module or of i3status if the module is an i3status one
+
+            sleep_delay = 0.25  # spotify need at least this
+            sleep_delay = 0.75  # transmission need at least this
+            sleep_delay = 1.0   # maybe external_script, getjson, etc?
+            time.sleep(sleep_delay)
+
             self.py3_wrapper.refresh_modules(module_name)
 
     def i3_msg(self, module_name, command):
```

Yes. The `dbus` command is long and bad so we do this in `spotify` instead. For other commands that are nice, they just don't have delay. Should we even have a `delay` config even if we have no need for it right now... and/or might not even be utilized much?

# BRAINSTORMING
```
on_click 1, 0.5 = 'exec ...'
```
```
on_click 1 = {
    'run': 'exec lxappearance'
    'delay': 0.5
}
```
```
on_click 1 = {
    'exec': 'lxappearance'   # an exec alias. nice prefix. idk.
    'delay': 0.5
}
```
",{},{}
