4004,IssuesEvent,2016-01-05 11:01:00+00:00,7433211,jmcnamara/XlsxWriter,94267,jmcnamara,,,closed,Chartsheet size does not match chart size,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jmcnamara/XlsxWriter/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jmcnamara/XlsxWriter/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': '009800'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jmcnamara/XlsxWriter/labels/short%20term', 'name': 'short term', 'color': '009800'}]",[],6,"Using XlsxWriter 0.5.5 and Python 2.7.6 in Windows 7 Professional 64-bit.  Using Microsoft Office Excel 2007 SP3.  When adding a chart to a chartsheet, the size of the chart doesn't match the size of the chartsheet.  The chart goes off the chartsheet to the right, causing the series labels to be cut-off from view.  The chart also doesn't fill the space at the bottom.  The chart dimensions do not match the chartsheet dimensions. The chart has to be manually resized in Excel to fit the chartsheet properly.

I tried changing the size (set_size) of the chart and this does nothing to affect this problem.

I opened the generated xlsx file using Microsoft Excel Viewer version 12 on a different machine with Windows Server 2008 R2 64-bit installed.  It exposes the same problem.

I used the following example chartsheet to reproduce the problem:
https://xlsxwriter.readthedocs.org/example_chartsheet.html

Using this example, the chart size comes out as 10.18"" wide X 6.65"" tall (Format tab).  After manually adjusting the chart to fit within the existing chartsheet, the chart size measures roughly 9.43"" wide X 6.84"" tall.

Here is another quick example that reproduces the problem:
```python
import xlsxwriter
workbook = xlsxwriter.Workbook('chartsheet.xlsx')
worksheet = workbook.add_worksheet()
chartsheet = workbook.add_chartsheet()
data = [10, 40, 50, 20, 10, 50]
worksheet.write_column('A1', data)
chart1 = workbook.add_chart({'type': 'line'})
chart1.add_series({'values':'=Sheet1!$A$1:$A$6'})
chartsheet.set_chart(chart1)
workbook.close()
```
It also produces a chart that is 10.18"" wide X 6.65"" tall and needs to be adjusted to fit:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7607056/3003389/89a7946c-dd51-11e3-9b3f-412e9a4b51b9.png)
After adjusting:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7607056/3003394/a6a40a96-dd51-11e3-92e0-a7020082afd9.png)
",{},{}
