5953,IssuesEvent,2015-08-01 17:57:38+00:00,12420595,CamDavidsonPilon/lifelines,884032,CamDavidsonPilon,,,closed,implement power and sample size analysis,[],[],4,"This could be useful for several reasons. In my use case, I have a large number of possible group assignments I could test with pairwise log-rank tests. However, I prefer to not test them all since I expect that a significant fraction of them stands no chance of being significant, because of insufficient sample sizes or numbers of deaths. Performing such tests would have no benefit but would dilute the results by increasing the amount of multiple-hypothesis correction. If instead I can rule many of these hopeless cases out a priori based on power/sample size analysis, I can avoid that problem. 

I'm new to survival statistics, so I hesitate to try my hand at helping code this, but I imagine that for an expert, implementing this for the log-rank test would not be very difficult. I have searched a bit and found proprietary statistical packages (Stata, SAS, etc) offering this feature. There are R packages, academic references and a few forum posts that seemed related but perhaps not exactly what I'm looking for.

Power and sample size analysis for survival regression would also be useful.",{},{}
5960,IssuesEvent,2017-12-29 02:30:34+00:00,28577939,CamDavidsonPilon/lifetimes,884032,CamDavidsonPilon,,,closed,conditional_expected_number_of_purchases_up_to_time shows weird values for ParetoNBDFitter,[],[],4,"It seems that conditional_expected_number_of_purchases_up_to_time method works weird for ParetoNBDFitter. Users with positive frequency and recency experience near zero estimate for predicted purchases, while those with frequency and recency =0 have higher values of predicted purchases. Not sure if it's a bug though, are you able to confirm?

You can easily replicate this with code below:
```python
from lifetimes.datasets import load_cdnow_summary
data = load_cdnow_summary(index_col=[0])

print(data.head())

from lifetimes import BetaGeoFitter
from lifetimes import ParetoNBDFitter

bgf = BetaGeoFitter(penalizer_coef=0.0) # 0.001 to 0.1 are effective (L2 regularization)
bgf.fit(data['frequency'], data['recency'], data['T'])
print(bgf)
pnbd = ParetoNBDFitter(penalizer_coef=0.0) # 0.001 to 0.1 are effective (L2 regularization)
pnbd.fit(data['frequency'], data['recency'], data['T'])
print(pnbd)

t = 30
data['pred_purchases_1m_bgf'] = bgf.conditional_expected_number_of_purchases_up_to_time(t, data['frequency'], data['recency'], data['T'])
data['pred_purchases_1m_pnbd'] = pnbd.conditional_expected_number_of_purchases_up_to_time(t, data['frequency'], data['recency'], data['T'])
print data.head(20)
```

![result](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17828920/32366921-851fb9e0-c080-11e7-9130-276fd74b0a3f.JPG)
",{},{}
