6540,IssuesEvent,2017-10-24 22:42:43+00:00,39119843,miguelgrinberg/python-socketio,262602,dfee,,,closed,request from aiohttp,"[{'id': 236452969, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/miguelgrinberg/python-socketio/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c', 'default': True}]",[],6,"Below I have two implementations of passing the aiohttp request to the AsyncNamespace methods. Are these methods fragile? Is there a better place upstream where I should be doing this? (i.e. will this work across all Managers?)

A wrapper that passes the aiohttp request.

```
from collections import OrderedDict
import functools
import inspect

import socketio


def pass_request(func):
    argspec = inspect.getargspec(func).args

    @functools.wraps(func)
    async def wrapper(namespace, *args):
        arg_map = OrderedDict(zip(argspec, (namespace, *args, None)))
        request = namespace.server.environ[arg_map['sid']]['aiohttp.request']
        arg_map['request'] = request
        rv = func(*arg_map.values())
        return await rv if inspect.isawaitable(rv) else rv
    return wrapper


class SocketNamesapce(socketio.AsyncNamespace):
    @pass_request
    def on_connect(self, sid, environ, request):
        # pylint: disable=no-self-use
        # pylint: disable=unused-argument
        print(""connect "", sid)

    def on_disconnect(self, sid):
        # pylint: disable=no-self-use
        print('disconnect ', sid)

    @pass_request
    async def on_message(self, sid, data, request):
        print(""message "", data)
        await self.emit('message', data, room=sid)
```

A subclass for AsyncNamespace that provide the request object if the method is requesting it.
```
class SocketNamesapce(socketio.AsyncNamespace):
    async def trigger_event(self, event, *args):
        handler_name = 'on_' + event
        callback = getattr(self, handler_name, None)
        if callback:
            argspec = inspect.getargspec(callback).args
            if 'request' in argspec:
                args = (*args, self.server.environ[args[0]]['aiohttp.request'])
        await super().trigger_event(event, *args)

    def on_connect(self, sid, environ, request):
        # pylint: disable=no-self-use
        # pylint: disable=unused-argument
        print('request', request)
        print(""connect "", sid)

    def on_disconnect(self, sid):
        # pylint: disable=no-self-use
        print('disconnect ', sid)

    async def on_message(self, sid, data, request):
        print('request', request)
        print(""message "", data)
        await self.emit('message', data, room=sid)
```",{},{}
6554,IssuesEvent,2016-11-08 13:56:14+00:00,39119843,miguelgrinberg/python-socketio,19623837,adsalpha,,,opened,Client not finding Socket.IO server,[],[],0,"I'm using Flask with uWSGI and NGINX, having set up the Socket.IO server as `sio = socketio.Server(async_mode='gevent_uwsgi', logger=True)`. The whole thing is running in a Docker container which listens on localhost port 3536.

