7578,IssuesEvent,2017-02-24 17:34:51+00:00,525316,mozilla/bleach,987487,kousu,131524,mozilla,opened,`bleach()` and `linkify()` should commute,[],[],0,"`linkify(clean(s)) != clean(linkify(s))` in all cases. `linkify` will undo at least some of the bleaching that `clean` did.

```
>>> import bleach
>>> bleach.__version__
u'1.5.0'
>>> s = '<p>http://example.com</p>'
>>> bleach.clean(s)
u'&lt;p&gt;http://example.com&lt;/p&gt;'
>>> # it's eaten the <p>, good bleach
... bleach.linkify(s)
u'<p><a href=""http://example.com"" rel=""nofollow"">http://example.com</a></p>'
>>> # it's made a link. good bleach!
... bleach.clean(bleach.linkify(s))
u'&lt;p&gt;<a href=""http://example.com"">http://example.com</a>&lt;/p&gt;'
>>> # it ate the <p> *and* it made a link. yum!
... # but what was bleach.clean(s) again?
>>> bleach.clean(s)
u'&lt;p&gt;http://example.com&lt;/p&gt;'
>>> bleach.linkify(bleach.clean(s))
u'<p><a href=""http://example.com"" rel=""nofollow"">http://example.com</a></p>'
>>> # it... put the <p> back
```

I expect this has something to do with `linkify()` calling an overeager-to-please `html5lib`.",{},{}
