7842,IssuesEvent,2017-04-20 21:54:02+00:00,35100117,neo4j/neo4j-python-driver,4567245,johnbodley,201120,neo4j,closed,ServiceUnavailable: Failed to read from closed connection after wait,[],[],2,"What causes Neo4j to close a connection? The following code,

```python
from neo4j.util import Watcher
from neo4j.v1 import GraphDatabase 
from time import sleep

Watcher(""neo4j.bolt"").watch()


def foo(driver):
    with driver.session() as session:
        results = session.run('MATCH (n) RETURN n LIMIT 10')
        for record in results:
            print record

driver = GraphDatabase.driver('bolt://localhost:7687')
foo(driver)
sleep(60)
foo(driver)
```
throws a `ServiceUnavailable` exception after the sleep, 
```
>>> foo(driver)
2017-04-19 14:25:01,197  C: RUN (u'MATCH (n) RETURN n LIMIT 10', {})
2017-04-19 14:25:01,198  C: PULL_ALL ()
2017-04-19 14:25:01,199  ~~ [CLOSE]
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""<stdin>"", line 5, in foo
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/neo4j/v1/api.py"", line 229, in __exit__
    self.close()
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/neo4j/v1/api.py"", line 261, in close
    self._disconnect(sync=True)
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/neo4j/v1/api.py"", line 244, in _disconnect
    self._connection.sync()
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/neo4j/bolt/connection.py"", line 325, in sync
    detail_delta, summary_delta = self.fetch()
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/neo4j/bolt/connection.py"", line 249, in fetch
    raise self.Error(""Failed to read from closed connection {!r}"".format(self.server.address))
neo4j.exceptions.ServiceUnavailable: Failed to read from closed connection Address(host='127.0.0.1', port= 7687)
```

Note however if I execute `foo(driver)` after the exception is thrown it reconnects and the connection re-inits and the run statement is successful.

The only remedy I know is to redefine the `GraphDatabase.driver` prior to calling `foo(...)` for the second time, though I'm unsure why this is necessary. As far as I can tell Bolt does't have a specified timeout. 

Note I'm using `neo4j-driver` v1.2.0 with Python 2.7, and Neo4j v3.1.0.",{},{}
