9139,IssuesEvent,2017-03-23 18:24:01+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,1315589,soupault,897180,scikit-image,closed,Possible bug in skimage.measure.label,"[{'id': 360216647, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/scikit-image/scikit-image/labels/status:%20needs%20decision', 'name': 'status: needs decision', 'color': 'fef2c0', 'default': False}]",[],3,"## Description
I have been working on labeling regions of a binary image.  The output is apparently correct if the number of regions is equal to 255 or less.  However, when running on an image with more regions, the method returns the correct count of the number of regions, but the labeled array it returns contains no labeled region numbered higher than 255.

I do not have a traceback for this, for the code is not throwing any errors.  It simply provides results which are incorrect.

## Way to reproduce
- [x] Code example
       data is an array of boolean values
       labeledData, labelCount = measure.label(data, return_num = True)

      The input data has thousands of isolated clusters of ""true"" values in it;
      the code returns a label count of 266345 for the input data, and that is
      a reasonable value.  However, the output array contains 254 clusters
      labeled 1 through 254, respectively.  All other clusters (266345 - 254 of them)
      are numbered '255'.  No errors of any kind are thrown.  I would call this a bug.
- [ ] Relevant images (if any)
- [x] Operating System -- Windows 7 Enterprise, 64-bit
- [x] Python version -- 2.7
- [x] scikit-image version (run `skimage.__version__`) -- '0.12.3'

",{},{}
