9785,IssuesEvent,2015-04-14 15:18:50+00:00,14829536,pydata/numexpr,314521,FrancescAlted,1284191,pydata,closed,expected gains with more threads not achieved,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pydata/numexpr/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],1,"I'm trying to do an in-place exp() on a very large (1 million x 100) 2D array. I see some improvement when using multiple threads, but after about 2 or 4 threads performance does not improve further (and actually sometimes gets noticeably worse).  I suppose I can expect diminishing returns for such a simple operation, but I'm hoping to understand whether this performance is expected or if there's anything I can change about my install/config that would provide further improvements.

Code
```
X = np.random.rand(1e6, 100)
starttime = time.time()
for trial in range(10):
    ne.evaluate('exp(X)', out=X)
elapsedtime = time.time() - starttime
```

Machine A has 64 total cores. AMD 1400 MHz  Here are timing results. They are reproduceable across several runs, and the ranking is similar when I make the input array X several times bigger.

------------------------------- 1 cores
0.85 sec/trial, 10 trials
------------------------------- 2 cores
0.75 sec/trial, 10 trials
------------------------------- 4 cores
0.98 sec/trial, 10 trials
------------------------------- 8 cores
1.11 sec/trial, 10 trials
------------------------------- 16 cores
0.64 sec/trial, 10 trials

Machine B has 16 total cores. Intel 2300 MHz. Here are timing results.
------------------------------- 1 cores
1.06 sec/trial, 10 trials
------------------------------- 2 cores
0.58 sec/trial, 10 trials
------------------------------- 4 cores
0.43 sec/trial, 10 trials
------------------------------- 8 cores
0.49 sec/trial, 10 trials
------------------------------- 16 cores
0.55 sec/trial, 10 trials

PS: thanks for such an awesome library. Even now, my code is way faster than just using plain-vanilla numpy.

",{},{}
