10442,IssuesEvent,2018-02-16 13:51:50+00:00,3470471,FortAwesome/Font-Awesome,132895,robmadole,1505683,FortAwesome,closed,Bug: Icon remains in DOM after class changed,"[{'id': 40531311, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/FortAwesome/Font-Awesome/labels/waiting%20for%20feedback', 'name': 'waiting for feedback', 'color': 'bfd4f2', 'default': False}]",[],4,"I am writing an Angular 5 application with a hamburger menu in the top nav. The intention is to display 'fa-bars' when the menu is closed, and 'fa-times' when the menu is open in order to provide some feedback to the user.

The menu's open/closed state is reflected by a boolean variable in my control: isCollapsed. The variable is true when the menu is closed and false when the menu is open.

The template is defined as follows:

```
  <button class=""navbar-toggler navbar-toggler-right float-right"" type=""button"" (click)=""isCollapsed = !isCollapsed"">
    <ng-container *ngIf=""isCollapsed""><i class=""fal fa-bars""></i></ng-container>
    <ng-container *ngIf=""!isCollapsed""><i class=""fal fa-times""></i></ng-container>
  </button>
```

However because FA5's js library is simply replacing the <i> tag with an <svg> tag in the DOM, every time I open or close the menu an additional representation of the icon appears. Clicking it several times, it looks like this:

===XXX

Is there a way to control which icon is displayed dynamically, or is an icon forever in the DOM once it is put there the first time?

Epilogue:  I was able to get the functionality I wanted by using SCSS and webfonts, rather than JS and SVGs. However this isn't how I would prefer to use FA5. So I have a workaround, but a proper fix is highly desired.",{},{}
