10729,IssuesEvent,2015-02-03 15:52:43+00:00,8030543,msgpack-rpc/msgpack-rpc-python,667876,huangwei1024,1770939,msgpack-rpc,opened,about strategy of socket closed ,[],[],0,"HI,
when `ClientSocket` was closed, I think the `Session._request_table` were no longer necessary.
`future` under current strategy will be wait until timeout, but if `Client` set timeout `None`, when socket closed, there will be endless wait.

```python
    def on_close(self, sock):
        # Avoid calling self.on_connect_failed after self.close called.
        if self._closed:
            return

        # if sock in self._sockets:
        #     self._sockets.remove(sock)
        #     self._connecting = 0
        # else:
        # Tornado does not have on_connect_failed event.
        self.on_connect_failed(sock)
```

What do you think?",{},{}
10747,IssuesEvent,2015-10-22 09:17:56+00:00,15510254,openfisca/openfisca-core,12686,cbenz,1794404,openfisca,closed,Usual way to distinguish formulas from input variables is broken,[],[],3,"We've been taught to use `column.formula_class is None` to detect if a column is an input variable.

However, after last Friday, this does not work anymore, as all columns seem to have a `formula_class` attribute. The [recently-introduced](https://github.com/openfisca/openfisca-core/commit/cd2299d6896d51906d2cb4ec34c6c456d56fd643) `is_input_variable` is the expected replacement, I suppose, but it does not seem to work (#328), and would [probably be reversed](https://github.com/openfisca/openfisca-core/commit/cd2299d6896d51906d2cb4ec34c6c456d56fd643#diff-31e80408104c8f43c6b796a369a77585R1116).

The current suggested replacement is to test for `column.function is None`, but this does not seem to be equivalent, as last week `salaire_net_a_payer` had a `formula_class`, but has no `function`. ",{},{}
