11753,IssuesEvent,2016-08-12 23:07:51+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,1883523,kwlzn,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,"investigate high memory utilization with v2 engine, daemon","[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/engine', 'name': 'engine', 'color': 'fbca04'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/pantsd', 'name': 'pantsd', 'color': 'd4c5f9'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/performance', 'name': 'performance', 'color': '0052cc'}]",[],0,"essentially, with a `./pants list ::` in our monorepo the rss of the daemon process stays on the order of 4-7GB and can balloon +/-.5..3GB on each subsequent run. this seems problematic on its own - but additionally, this sheer size seems to cause a noticeable pause when `DaemonPantsRunner` forks. afaict, approximately 20% of the time of a `./pants list ::` is spent just forking.

this [screen cap](https://asciinema.org/a/4qzul93k5svt07bf6i67dvd2u) demonstrates the crux of the problem, as captured by `ps`. the capture starts with a primed daemon and then illustrates the memory behavior of multiple subsequent `./pants list ::` executed via the daemon and the symptom of a pause which is correlated with a ballooning memory footprint of the forked process.
",{},{}
11760,IssuesEvent,2016-07-21 01:33:26+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,157586,jsirois,3065172,pantsbuild,closed,`--binaries-baseurls` should support file urls,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/in-progress', 'name': 'in-progress', 'color': '009800'}]","[{'login': 'jsirois', 'id': 157586, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/157586?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/jsirois', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jsirois/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",3,"I think this means the [`Fetcher`](https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/master/src/python/pants/net/http/fetcher.py#L21) should support them out of the box.

Since we don't support this today, you have to do more work than you should to depend on local binaries (or binaries mounted via NFS for example). See here for an example of the extra work (Context is Aurora): https://gist.github.com/jsirois/f4ea2167f397e544549edbdea005581c",{},{}
11771,IssuesEvent,2016-11-03 18:17:31+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,46740,stuhood,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,Zero-arg intrinsics (and/or: Subsystem support),"[{'id': 284599650, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/1.0.0', 'name': '1.0.0', 'color': 'c7def8', 'default': False}, {'id': 268094252, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/engine', 'name': 'engine', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}]",[],0,"To inject ""Subsystem"" dependencies to rules in the new engine, we currently use SelectLiteral. The downside of this is that the creator of the rule needs a literal instance of the Subsystem type (at which point they could theoretically just alias it in an error prone fashion).

Rather than `SelectLiteral(value, Type)`, we should add zero-arg providers of singletons/Subsystems so that they can be retrieved directly by a consumer with `Select(Type)`.

cc @baroquebobcat ",{},{}
11777,IssuesEvent,2015-08-24 17:02:37+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,157586,jsirois,3065172,pantsbuild,reopened,Python Thrift caching issue with included Thrift files,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/user%20reported', 'name': 'user reported', 'color': '5319e7'}]",[],10,"Test case available on the `thrift-include` branch of https://github.com/wyattanderson/pantstest/tree/thrift-include

### Problem
Under-invalidation when modifying transitive Thrift dependencies of a Thrift target. We have a Thrift API in `A.thrift` that imports `B.thrift` and `C.thrift`. `B` and `C` are consumable via separate targets as well. `A` depends on `B` and `C` in the BUILD file in addition to importing them:

```
python_thrift_library(
    name='A',
    sources=[
        'A.thrift',
    ],
    dependencies=[
        ':B',
        ':C',
    ]
)

python_thrift_library(
    name='B',
    sources=[
        'B.thrift',
    ]
)

python_thrift_library(
    name='C',
    sources=[
        'C.thrift',
    ]
)
```

The most reliable reproducer I can find is **in a project with artifact caching enabled, make a change to `C.thrift` and run/build a Python target that depends on `A.thrift`. The changes won't be picked up unless you `clean-all`**.

### Setup
1. Clone the repository
1. `./pants binary src/python:test && dist/test.pex`
1. Expected output: 

        ['C', 'read', 'thrift_spec', 'validate', 'write']
1. Uncomment lines 5-7 in `src/thrift/C.thrift`
1. `./pants binary src/python:test && dist/test.pex`

### Expected output 
    ['C', 'Cba', 'Cfoo', 'Cfoobar', 'read', 'thrift_spec', 'validate', 'write']

### Actual output
    ['C', 'read', 'thrift_spec', 'validate', 'write']

If you run `./pants clean-all`, you get the expected output, which makes me think this is an artifact caching issue. The actual problem we're seeing in production is even stranger: the addition of a new type to the equivalent of the `C.thrift` file doesn't get included in the built PEX.",{},{}
