12552,IssuesEvent,2016-06-28 19:50:45+00:00,3791384,coursera-dl/coursera-dl,212145,rbrito,5588942,coursera-dl,opened,Document how to run the script under Windows,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/coursera-dl/coursera-dl/labels/documentation-needed', 'name': 'documentation-needed', 'color': '0052cc'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/coursera-dl/coursera-dl/labels/help-needed', 'name': 'help-needed', 'color': 'eb6420'}]",[],0,"To test this darned long-names thing under Windows, I went through the trouble of:

1. selling my soul :grinning:
2. downloading a Windows 10 ISO image directly from Microsoft
3. installing it on a virtual machine
4. installing Python 3.5

And everything was fine.

Using `pip` was super easy. But I have no idea where/how to actually *run* coursera-dl, after installing it with `--user`. All I got was something like ""command not found"" and the oficial Python documentation is less than stellar here.

If I install ipython the same way, I *can* run an ipython console, which means that something is being done differently between the two projects.

Since I'm not that motivated to go further, It would help a lot if our Windows users could document what they did, so that we can have an appropriate section in our manual on how to use Windows.

Please, help spread the word to whomever can help with the documentation (twitter, facebook, mailing lists etc.). All the credits will be given with pull requests.
",{},{}
