12755,IssuesEvent,2015-08-26 19:02:32+00:00,4744355,soft-matter/trackpy,1430861,apiszcz,5857177,soft-matter,opened,linking observation and sensitivity to velocity span,[],[],0,"I observed a false positive trajectory labeling situation and wonder if there is a parameter to mitigate the situation (maintain a single track). I'm using adaptive and velocity linking. With velocity span set  as shown below I get a variety of trajectory labeling results. Is it the case that velocity linking is expecting all particles to be moving a similar speed?

Case#1:
Each point exists within its own frame, single trajectory is labelled (correct)

Case#2:
I set two records from above to the same frame and time value near the middle of the data set, and now I see two trajectories. It is a single trajectory that is being split into two when it encounters two records nearby in the same frame. I made the astop << 10% of the gap between the samples. astep is 0.99. Here is the result

    velocity span, # of trajectories
    0, 2
    1, 1
    2, 2
    3, 1
    4, 3
    5, 3 with gap 

 This is a toy problem with a single particle at a relatively constant speed. If I have multiple particles at different speeds I'm wondering what options I have to reduce these false positive splits.

",{},{}
