12891,IssuesEvent,2015-09-02 00:04:40+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,1360539,bacongobbler,6117407,deis,closed,Router not respecting domains when routing traffic (app name/subdomain only?),"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/router', 'name': 'router', 'color': 'bfdadc'}]",[],7,"Setup: Deis deployed to a private subnet in AWS with an internal load balancer and a private hosted zone `services-staging.internal`.
By configuring a second public ELB `external-service.my-services.com` to point to the same Deis instances it is possible to access applications via the Deis router even if custom domains are not configured.

The intent here was to expose a limited set of apps via the public ELB and restrict all other apps to the private subnet.

See below for example calls via the IP address of the public external ELB by modifying the Host Header.

It appears the router is not honoring either the main Deis domain or the apps custom domains when routing traffic to the ""internal-service"" app.

Is this expected behavior?


````Shell
$ deisctl config platform get domain
services-staging.internal

$ deis domains -a internal-service
=== internal-service Domains
No domains

$ dig +short external-service.my-services.com
52.5.110.243
107.23.169.20
````

````Shell
$ curl 52.5.110.243 -H ""Host: internal-service.services-staging.internal""
{""msg"":""hello from service""}

$ curl 52.5.110.243 -H ""Host: internal-service.my-services.com""
{""msg"":""hello from service""}

$ curl 52.5.110.243 -H ""Host: internal-service.other""
{""msg"":""hello from service""}
````

I would have expected `internal-service` app to *only* be accessible via the `internal-service.services-staging.internal` domain and not be accessible via any other domain.",{},{}
