13106,IssuesEvent,2017-10-08 05:48:49+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,138060,rainwoodman,6392739,conda,opened,Feature Request: relocated conda environments,[],[],0,"I propose adding an argument `--dest-dir` to `conda create`.

The argument specifies an alternative location of the environment other than the intended `prefix`.

Here is an example:
```
conda create -n env -p /opt/my-python-application --dest-dir=$TMP/buildroot/ python=3.6
```
This will write the the conda environment to $TMP/buildroot, but when these files are copied to `/opt/my-python-application` it will run as is.

One potential use-case is to create linux distribution packages (e.g. RPM) of entire conda environments; can simplify for example to create Rolls of certain computing environments for RocksClusters.

The package builders usually require the installation script to have such a feature like autotools' `DESTDIR`, because the assumption is that the builder does not otherwise have access to the intended target directory of installation. For example, rpmbuild prefixes make install with DESTDIR to allow non-root building and automatic packaging of files from the install-root. (see https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/How_to_create_an_RPM_package#.25install_section )

In addition, we have another use case for deployment of conda environments on HPC systems, but it may be too specialized to be mentioned here.

I suppose this is a trivial change -- if hopefully it doesn't get into the way of the path-fixers.",{},{}
13107,IssuesEvent,2017-01-01 18:50:32+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,23440318,TheMitchWorksPro,6392739,conda,opened,conda update --all killed a Win7 64bit installation of anaconda that worked previously,[],[],0,"Background: 
* I had installed Anaconda months ago with a default of Python 3.5 and additional environment of Python 2.7.  This was done on a Windows 7 64 bit laptop w/ 1.4 Ghz processor, 16 Gigs of Ram and ample HD space
* Spyder stopped working for no reason.  only known change between then and now:  Windows updates.
* in attempting to debug this, ran across something that suggested maybe I needed to update my Python 3.5 environment in which it was originally deployed

What happened
* ran ""conda update --all"" on my 3.5 Python environment
* now that environment is missing from my notebook menus 
* and all icons relating to the default 3.5 environment are gone
* and the activate.bat and activate script and missing from the Anaconda3 default env folder
* and anaconda command prompt does not work now (error says the batch file is missing)
* it appears I now cannot use my Anaconda3 env - only the secondary Python 27 env is working

What I would like from you
* Please look into what caused this error.  It is a bad user experience when you take a step that should ensure your environment is up to date and instead it kills your environment

In the interim:
* problems with Spyder, this bad experience with 3.5, and an upcoming class that will be taught in 2.7 have convinced me to re-install my whole environment this time as a 2.7 distribution with an extra 3.x environment.  I may try 3.6 that I think is out instead of 3.5 - but this behavior is worrisome as it indicates the update command can kill a working distribution.

Here are all the messages from running of ""conda update --all"" on my environment showing what it did up until the problems occurred:

