13357,IssuesEvent,2017-08-29 14:47:21+00:00,97101009,elastic/apm-agent-python,93675,beniwohli,6764390,elastic,opened,Investigate options to support Twisted,[],[],0,"We currently don't support any asynchronous Python frameworks like Twisted, Tornado & Co. Supporting these frameworks is inherently difficult due to the fact that we made a lot of design decisions on the assumption that a thread only handles a single request at a time. This is not true for async frameworks.

There are some ways we could achieve at least some support for Twisted by storing data of the current transaction on the request handler instead of a thread local. Similar workarounds may or may not exist for other async frameworks.

In the future, we may be able to use execution contexts as proposed by [PEP 550](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0550/), but this will take some time until it is available.",{},{}
13365,IssuesEvent,2017-12-07 04:37:13+00:00,9801644,elastic/elasticsearch-py,1194751,uovobw,6764390,elastic,closed,index() method appears to only always update/overwrite,[],[],3,"Greetings, this might be a false positive due to my scarse knowledge of ES, but i am not being able to perform a simple insert.

To provide a bit of context i have a flask application that has an [after_request](http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/0.12/api/#flask.Flask.after_request) that i use to send to elasticsearch a number of info about the request itself.

```
# import lines omitted for clarity
# i can create the elasticsearch client within or without the decorator function and the behaviour does not change
es = Elasticsearch(hosts=[""my_host:myport""], ca_certs=certifi.where())
document = {
     ""some"" : ""fields"",
     ""and"": {
          ""other"": ""nested"",
     },
}
es.indices.create(index=""my_index"", ignore=400)
es.index(index=""my_index"", doc_type=""same_doc_type"", body=document)
```

as expected i get `created: True` on the first invokation.

After the first invokation (i can appear to only set a given doc_type once) each time I change the document structure deeply and try to insert again (ie: the next flask request) i get a `created: False` and the document is ""overwritten"" (even if i restart my service, that makes me think of an error in the way the request is sent) every time.

This sounds like a logical error in the way i am using the library, i have checked that the `create` function has recently been modified to force the use of an id and that the `index` one now can omit the id parameter to have one created on the server.

Finally, i am running python3 in a virtualenv, using elasticsearch on aws2 (version 5.5), and the library as specified in the readme, elasticsearch>=5.0.0,<6.0.0

Thanks for the attention
",{},{}
13368,IssuesEvent,2015-08-31 21:53:08+00:00,9801644,elastic/elasticsearch-py,12726639,shashank-moengage,6764390,elastic,opened,"Change the mapping of field, when data is not present for that field?",[],[],0,"Hi,

Suppose I have a field in an index whose mapping is not yet defined and hence is assigned dynamically.
Now, I added a datapoint with that field but the data type assigned is not the type I wanted it to be.
I deleted that datapoint. Is there a way to delete the mapping for that specific field when there is no datapoint containing that field? I don't want to reindex the index",{},{}
