I found a problem that the blockblockservice _logs_ an error (does not throw one) when exists() is called on a non-existing file.

```
from azure.storage.blob import BlockBlobService

storage_name = ""xxxx""
account_key = ""yyyyy""
blob_name = ""zzzzz""

blob_service = BlockBlobService(account_name=storage_name, account_key=storage_key)
print(blob_service.exists(blob_name, ""does_not_exist""))
```

This produces the following output:
```
ERROR:azure.storage.common.storageclient:Client-Request-ID=2ddaedf3-1d2c-11e8-af2e-4ce173460adf Retry policy did not allow for a retry: Server-Timestamp=Thu, 01 Mar 2018 08:40:27 GMT, Server-Request-ID=2881fe87-201e-012f-2738-b16ad6000000, HTTP status code=404, Exception=The specified blob does not exist.ErrorCode: BlobNotFound.
False
```
While the correct answer (`False`) is given, the logged error is unexpected.

Is this the intended behaviour?",{},{}
