13753,IssuesEvent,2017-03-29 18:21:55+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,973454,arthurdarcet,7049303,aio-libs,closed,Memory leak in head get requests over SSL,[],[],25,"I'm trying to track down a memory leak but I not having much luck… Could you have a look?

Here is the leaking code:
```python
import resource, gc

last = 0
def mem(*_):
    gc.collect()
    global last
    mem = resource.getrusage(resource.RUSAGE_SELF).ru_maxrss / 1024
    print('Variation:', mem - last, 'ko')
    last = mem


import asyncio, aiohttp

async def main():
   conn = aiohttp.TCPConnector(verify_ssl=False)
   session = aiohttp.ClientSession(connector=conn)
   url = 'https://127.0.0.1:8081'

   mem()
   for _ in range(3000):
       async with session.head(url):
           pass
       mem()

asyncio.get_event_loop().run_until_complete(main())
```

I'm using this https server to test:
```python
import ssl, asyncio
from aiohttp import web

async def handle(request):
    await request.read()
    return web.Response(text='ok')

app = web.Application()
app.router.add_get('/', handle)
handler = app.make_handler()

sslcontext = ssl.SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23)
# openssl req  -nodes -new -x509  -keyout server.key -out server.cert
sslcontext.load_cert_chain('server.cert', 'server.key')

loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()
loop.run_until_complete(loop.create_server(handler, '0.0.0.0', 8081, ssl=sslcontext))
loop.run_forever()
```


The first script leaks around 30ko of RAM for every requests (between 8ko and 60ko)

From what i see with objgraph / pympler, the leaking object are `ResponseHandler`s. Not sure why they aren't garbage collected though.",{},{}
13771,IssuesEvent,2018-04-28 11:00:15+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,1778004,vovanz,7049303,aio-libs,opened,Documentation refers to a non-existing method `MultipartWriter.serialize()`,[],[],0,"## Long story short

[Working with Multipart](https://docs.aiohttp.org/en/stable/multipart.html) documentation page refers to `MultipartWriter.serialize()` method several times.

But this method does not exist (anymore?) in the [class aiohttp.MultipartWriter](https://docs.aiohttp.org/en/stable/multipart_reference.html#aiohttp.MultipartWriter).

## Expected behaviour

Methods mentioned in docs should actually exist :)

## Actual behaviour

`MultipartWriter.serialize()` is mentioned in docs but does not exist.

## Steps to reproduce

1. Open the ""[Working with Multipart](https://docs.aiohttp.org/en/stable/multipart.html)"" page in docs and CTRL+F all `MultipartWriter.serialize()` occurrences.
2. Open [aiohttp.MultipartWriter reference](https://docs.aiohttp.org/en/stable/multipart_reference.html#aiohttp.MultipartWriter) and make sure that this method is not documented there.
3. Open [the source at aiohttp/multipart.py](https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/1ba7bf10bbf46ff218bbfe57864a9eaa82fba589/aiohttp/multipart.py#L631) and make sure that the `serialize` method is not defined.

## Your environment

`aiohttp==3.1.3`",{},{}
