14188,IssuesEvent,2018-01-19 14:43:07+00:00,52009226,Duke-GCB/DukeDSClient,1024463,johnbradley,7875151,Duke-GCB,opened,Prevent Delivery to users without email addresses,[],[],0,"## Problem
There are some DukeDS users do not have email addresses in the DukeDS database.
D4S2 requires an email address to send the acceptance link to.
Otherwise the project transfer cannot be accepted.
This has caused issues within D4S2:
https://github.com/Duke-GCB/D4S2/issues/96
https://github.com/Duke-GCB/D4S2/issues/98

## Solution
We should check that the user actually has an email before attempting a share or delivery.
If so we can print an error message requesting that the user contact DukeDS to get the database fixed. As a work around the user could manually add the user to the project.
",{},{}
14195,IssuesEvent,2018-04-30 02:42:02+00:00,27082457,HIPS/autograd,7723126,mohit-surana,7935606,HIPS,opened,Convergence criteria for optimizers,[],[],0,"Many optimization frameworks provide an optional argument - `tol` or `tolerance` that lets one stop optimization if the function, gradient or parameter does not change much for a given iteration. This is used in conjunction with a parameter `max_iter` for a hard upper bound on the number of iterations the optimizer is to be run for.

The [optimizers in the autograd package](https://github.com/HIPS/autograd/blob/master/autograd/misc/optimizers.py) currently do not support this.

1) Are there plans of implementing this functionality?
2) If not, would it be a good idea for me to go ahead and implement this or do you feel that the increased computational complexity isn't worth it?

Thanks and great work on the package. Just used this for an assignment and it is really powerful!
A more navigable documentation would be great though.",{},{}
14218,IssuesEvent,2015-10-08 17:46:22+00:00,24777832,galaxyproject/planemo,63959,peterjc,7937847,galaxyproject,opened,Multiple install directories for planemo dependency_script?,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/galaxyproject/planemo/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],0,"The initial ``planemo dependency_script`` implementation f798c7e (see #303 and #310) produces a single ``dep_install.sh`` and ``env.sh`` script even when called on multiple ``tool_dependencies.xml`` files. The simplistic usage model is to run ``bash dep_install.sh`` and ``source env.sh`` prior to running Galaxy or any Galaxy tests.

Issue #319 addresses where to put a separate ``env.sh`` scripts for each tool under the ``tool_dependency_dir`` folder set in ``galaxy.ini`` or via ``planemo test --tool_dependency_dir <dep_dir> ...``

This issue is about a similar approach for where to put the files created by the installation itself, i.e. automatically adjusting the ``$INSTALL_DIR`` for multiple ``tool_dependencies.xml`` files. This would allow co-installation of clashing filenames (e.g. multiple versions of MIRA or BLAST).

Motivating example https://github.com/peterjc/galaxy_mira/commit/0d41761e7073f8fac4c9a4b2a34a95e839ef76f1 and https://travis-ci.org/peterjc/galaxy_mira/builds/84351148 - in this case ``planemo dependency_script`` is used on three ``tool_dependencies.xml`` files to install three versions of MIRA. The clashing binary name ``mira`` requires installation into separate folders and has implications for determining priority on ``$PATH`` (which would be addressed by #319). The workaround as shown is to call ``planemo dependency_script`` three times in a particular order.",{},{}
