14488,IssuesEvent,2017-02-27 14:25:13+00:00,8928074,PyCQA/baron,511258,nilshamerlinck,8749848,PyCQA,opened,Unexpected token issues triggered by a comment,[],[],0,"First case:
```
class Test(object):
    def test(self):
        # IF True
        if True:
            print True
        # ELSE
        else:
            print False
```

Triggers:
```
baron.parser.ParsingError: Error, got an unexpected token NAME here:

   1 class Test(object):
   2     def test(self):
   3         # IF True
   4         if True:
   5             print True<---- here
```

Second case:

```
class Test(object):
    def test(self):
        # IF True
        if True:
            if True:
                test = True
            else:
                test = False
        # ELSE
        else:
            print False
```

Triggers:
```
baron.parser.ParsingError: Error, got an unexpected token ELSE here:

   3         # IF True
   4         if True:
   5             if True:
   6                 test = True
   7             else:
   8                 test = False
   9         # ELSE
  10         else<---- here
```

Both snippets are parsed without error if I remove the second comment:
```
        # ELSE
```",{},{}
14491,IssuesEvent,2017-08-27 19:29:48+00:00,18508013,PyCQA/pyflakes,1235108,myint,8749848,PyCQA,closed,Does not detect used/unused modules within packages,"[{'id': 614822860, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/PyCQA/pyflakes/labels/duplicate', 'name': 'duplicate', 'color': 'cccccc', 'default': True}]",[],1,"pyflakes does not raise any errors on the following code:
```
import foo.bar
import foo.baz

foo.bar.fn()
foo.bang.fn()
```
despite the fact that `foo.baz` is an unused import, and `foo.bang` is not imported at all.

Is this behavior intentional?  Is there a way to modify pyflakes so it would warn in (ideally) both cases?

Thanks,
craig",{},{}
14516,IssuesEvent,2018-07-18 12:55:10+00:00,45935272,SatelliteQE/betelgeuse,48132,elyezer,8754276,SatelliteQE,opened,Make Betelgeuse Python 3.6+ only,[],[],0,"I am opening this issue to collect usage and plan when Betelgeuse will be Python 3.6+ only.

The only dependency that Betelgeuse has that blocks it to be py3 only is pylarion which is py2 only, Betelgeuse code base should be py3 already or will require minimum changes though.

That said, the plan will be to drop pylarion as dependency and with that the commands  `test-plan` and `requirement` will be gone. But the benefit is that Betelgeuse will be able to take advantage of new Python's features such as the asyncio which will make faster to collect test cases and parse large jUnit files.

Also Python 2.7 won't be maintained anymore past 2020 https://pythonclock.org/.

Have in mind that you can always install an old version of Betelgeuse if you need Python 2 support when the migration happens but I highly recommend you taking time and consider upgrading your code to Python 3 and using all the great features that the new version offers.",{},{}
