14901,IssuesEvent,2016-02-09 04:57:04+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,479213,pde,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,Test the renewer in integration tests,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/renewal', 'name': 'renewal', 'color': 'bfe5bf'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/testing', 'name': 'testing', 'color': 'bfe5bf'}]",[],2,"Currently, integration tests run `letsencrypt-renewer` but they currently don't test anything other than making sure the renewer doesn't error out. The comment [here](https://github.com/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/blob/master/tests/boulder-integration.sh#L59) says this is because the renewer fails the test which is at least partially due to #1949.",{},{}
14920,IssuesEvent,2015-12-03 23:33:09+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,479213,pde,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,Webroot authentication fails when no domains are specified,[],[],1,"If no domains are specified in `cli.ini` or on commandline (e.g. when using a `--csr` option, as the two are mutually exclusive), the process fails with the error `PluginError: --webroot-path must be set`, even if the option is set in the configuration file or passed on commandline.

If a list of domains is passed instead of a `csr` file, or if `manual` auth is used instead of `webroot`, the process completes successfully.

This is the (uncommented and sanitized) config file I used:
##### cli.ini
```
rsa-key-size = 4096
server = https://acme-staging.api.letsencrypt.org/directory
email = address@example.com

authenticator = webroot
webroot-path = /var/www/html/default

csr = /etc/letsencrypt/csr.der
```

And this is the log file:
##### /var/log/letsencrypt/letsencrypt.log.4
```
