15735,IssuesEvent,2016-10-29 09:44:09+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,20593743,tddsg,11668813,Z3Prover,opened,Problem when setting timeout for Z3 with OCaml interface,[],[],0,"Hi there,

I'm using Z3 with OCaml interface and when trying to set a timeout for Z3, I encounter the following problem:

> WARNING: unknown parameter 'timeout'
> Legal parameters are:
>   auto_config (bool) (default: true)
>   debug_ref_count (bool) (default: false)
>   dump_models (bool) (default: false)
>   model (bool) (default: true)
>   model_validate (bool) (default: false)
>   proof (bool) (default: false)
>   rlimit (unsigned int) (default: 4294967295)
>   smtlib2_compliant (bool) (default: false)
>   timeout (unsigned int) (default: 4294967295)
>   trace (bool) (default: false)
>   trace_file_name (string) (default: z3.log)
>   type_check (bool) (default: true)
>   unsat_core (bool) (default: false)
>   well_sorted_check (bool) (default: false)

According to the error message, I think that the ""timeout"" parameter is correct, as it is reported that ""timeout (unsigned int) (default: 4294967295)""

Do you know why Z3 reports this error?

I'm using Z3 4.4.1 on Linux, and the OCaml code that I used to set timeout is:

```
  let ctx_config = [(""model"", ""false"");
                    (""proof"", ""false"");
                    (""timeout"", ""10000"")] in
  let ctx = Z3.mk_context ctx_config in
  ...
```

Thanks for taking your time to look at this issue!
",{},{}
15736,IssuesEvent,2018-01-02 16:10:03+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3085284,NikolajBjorner,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,Feature Request: Support Enumerating Solutions (without restarting),[],[],1,"The z3 CLI tool does not have a way to enumerate multiple possible solutions. There have been suggestions to just iteratively add constraints to exclude previous solutions, but since that would require rerunning the entire model from scratch every time, is extremely inefficient.",{},{}
15737,IssuesEvent,2017-08-03 10:18:49+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,1413005,florianschanda,11668813,Z3Prover,opened,"rounding on conversion to unsigned (fp.to_ubv, RNE)",[],[],0,"Hi Christoph,

```
(set-info :smt-lib-version 2.6)
(set-info :license |https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.html|)
(set-logic QF_FPBV)
(set-info :source |Florian Schanda|)
(set-info :category crafted)
(set-info :status unsat)

(define-const x Float32 ((_ to_fp 8 24) RNE (- 0.5)))
(define-const y (_ BitVec 8) ((_ fp.to_ubv 8) RNE x))
(define-const z (_ BitVec 8) #x00)

(assert (distinct y z))
(check-sat)
(exit)
```

This is  bit of a corner-case. The way I read IEEE suggest to me that even and odd when converting to integer refers to the integer, not the floating-point bit-pattern. So, -.5 should round to zero (since that is the nearest even number, not -1) and since 0 is representable in an unsigned bitvector the result should be 0 and not unspecified.",{},{}
15738,IssuesEvent,2017-06-22 18:00:05+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,511795,delcypher,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,"undefined reference to `lean::dense_matrix<rational, rational>::dense_matrix(unsigned int, unsigned int)'",[],[],1,"I just tried compiling `master` (@ 77ffa9f32fa5a202b95a7b2b745e608969ec9309) with CMake (Ninja generator with Debug build type) and with Clang (4.0) and ASan enabled (set environment variable `CXXFLAGS=""-fsanitize=address -fno-omit-frame-pointer""` in environment before configuring) and I get a linking error I haven't seen before.

```
src/util/lp/CMakeFiles/lp.dir/lu_instances.cpp.o: In function `lean::dense_matrix<rational, rational> lean::get_B<rational, rational>(lean::lu<rational, rational>&, vector<unsigned int, true, unsigned int> const&)':
/home/dan/dev/jfs/z3/src/src/util/lp/lu.hpp:935: undefined reference to `lean::dense_matrix<rational, rational>::dense_matrix(unsigned int, unsigned int)'
clang-4.0: error: linker command failed with exit code 1 (use -v to see invocation)            
ninja: build stopped: subcommand failed.       
```

@levnach I think this is your code. Any idea what's going on here?

I took a look and I think it's complaining about this template instantiation.

```c++
template lean::dense_matrix<lean::mpq, lean::mpq> lean::get_B<lean::mpq, lean::mpq>(lean::lu<lean::mpq, lean::mpq>&, vector<unsigned int> const&);
```

It looks like `lean::mpq` is a typedef for `rational` (see `src/util/lp/numeric_pair.h`). I think the constructor it's trying to call is

```c++
template <typename T, typename X> dense_matrix<T, X>::dense_matrix(unsigned m, unsigned n) : m_m(m), m_n(n), m_values(m * n, numeric_traits<T>::zero()) {
}
```

in `src/util/lp/dense_matrix.hpp`.

**EDIT:** ~~If I build without ASan I don't get the linker error which is weird.~~ I made a mistake. The a non-ASan Clang debug fails too.",{},{}
