15984,IssuesEvent,2016-02-27 05:56:57+00:00,37496521,nteract/nteract,836375,rgbkrk,12401040,nteract,closed,zmq for everyone,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nteract/nteract/labels/%C3%98MQ', 'name': 'ØMQ', 'color': 'ff0000'}]",[],6,"In order to connect to any Jupyter kernel, they rely on zmq for reliable interprocess communication. The node bindings, which are quite stable (and awesome), are a bit persnickety to install on some platforms (as with anything relying on native bindings to C). In order for a developer to build, e.g., an Electron app that relies on zmq, they tend to need these items:

* zmq headers
* (optionally) libsodium for encryption
* C compiler
* pkg-config
* for every version of Electron and node that come out, these need to be rebuilt
* rebuild for each version

[Releasing multiplatform precompiled binaries for node modules is completely doable](http://cylonjs.com/blog/2014/11/19/creating-multiplatform-precompiled-binaries-for-node-modules/), though care has to be taken to allow users to use their local version of libzmq + libsodium as well.

If you dig through issues on zmq, you'll find quite a few about [installation issues](https://github.com/JustinTulloss/zeromq.node/issues/360). Currently there are bundled Windows binaries *in* the repository for libzmq (for linking against).",{},{}
15985,IssuesEvent,2017-12-26 20:49:19+00:00,37496521,nteract/nteract,2482408,mpacer,12401040,nteract,opened,[play] editor's highlighting language should match kernel language after switching ,[],[],0,"Right now we don't have the language being extracted and propagated up to the CodeMirrorEditor component; it's just hardcoded: 
https://github.com/nteract/nteract/blob/cef76af981463d34758abec82c8cc913d444a4d4/applications/play/components/Main.js#L172

If I'm thinking about this correctly, we probably want to store this in the `currentKernel` entity.

I'm not sure what pattern is best to accomplish this though (since the relevant info is deeply nested inside `currentServer.kernelSpecs.kernelSpecByKernelName.[currentKernelName].spec.language`)… I suppose I can look at the pattern used for `currentKernelName`?",{},{}
