17692,IssuesEvent,2018-02-17 11:55:20+00:00,59214089,SCIP-Interfaces/PySCIPOpt,1506995,mattmilten,19473229,SCIP-Interfaces,reopened,ReOptimization,[],"[{'login': 'mattmilten', 'id': 1506995, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars3.githubusercontent.com/u/1506995?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/mattmilten', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mattmilten/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",5,"It would be nice to be able to use the re-optimization features of SCIP in the API.  I attempted this myself, and it was a simple enough matter to do
scip.setBoolParam(""reoptimization/enable"",True)
and also fairly straightforward to modify the .pyx and .pxd files to import SCIPfreeReoptSolve()

But when I tried to implement SCIPchgReoptObjective() it was not going well.  There is a difference in how it is called versus the current implementation of Model.SetObjective().  SCIPchgReoptObjective asks for all variables and coefficients all at once, but the current implementation of Model.SetObjective goes through each variable one at a time, so I cannot simply modify the existing code.",{},{}
17709,IssuesEvent,2018-01-02 22:25:29+00:00,19358488,mozilla-releng/redo,1474114,fredfortier,19614164,mozilla-releng,opened,Pass exceptions to the `cleanup` method,[],[],0,"I'm not sure what's the optimal implementation for this but I'd like to see what's happening in the logs when a `retry` is necessary. The `cleanup` function is nice but I'd like to access the exception in order to print in in my warning message. I'm not sure that I'm suggesting the best design but I'd like to achieve this function. I understand that I can put`try...except` inside on my `foo` function but I'd rather not have to.
```
        bar = retry(
            action=foo,
            attempts=5,
            sleeptime=5,
            retry_exceptions=(MyCustomError,),
            cleanup=lambda: log.warn('Trying the operation again. But why did it fail?'))
```",{},{}
