17857,IssuesEvent,2017-09-22 07:46:26+00:00,1732211,FactoryBoy/factory_boy,694541,rbarrois,20368050,FactoryBoy,closed,Django: Custom attributes for the Factory class,"[{'id': 30490576, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/FactoryBoy/factory_boy/labels/Q&A', 'name': 'Q&A', 'color': 'DDDDDD', 'default': False}]",[],1,"Hello! Thanks for the wonderful library!

I would like to do something like
```python
class UserFactory(factory.DjangoModelFactory):
    
    PASSWORD_LENGTH = 10
    password = factory.PostGenerationMethodCall(
                   'set_password', factory.Faker('password', length=PASSWORD_LENGTH))

    class Meta:
        model = User
```

But it raises _""factory/django.py, line 165, in __create TypeError: 'PASSWORD_LENGTH' is an invalid keyword argument for this function.""_.

Is there a way to define attributes for a class that are **not related** to the model?
Can the library ignore fields starting with '_' or '__', for example?

Temporary solution
```python
class CustomAttrsMixin(factory.Factory):

    class Meta:
        abstract = True

    @classmethod
    def _create(cls, model_class, *args, **kwargs):
        for attr, attr_value in kwargs.copy().items():
            if attr.startswith('_'):
                del kwargs[attr]

        # noinspection PyProtectedMember
        return super()._create(model_class, *args, **kwargs)
```


In addition, you can use inheritance
```python
class UserWithAttrs(UserFactory):
    _password = '15$Gs42h#8'     # <- This will not cause an exception when UserWithAttrs()
```",{},{}
17907,IssuesEvent,2018-03-23 04:09:21+00:00,102973646,fastai/fastai,2786927,raspstephan,20547620,fastai,opened,Inconsistency in dim ordering between ImageClassifierData.from_arrays and PyTorch models,[],[],0,"The issue is illustrated here: https://gist.github.com/raspstephan/df9bb81b954851e723938d74427c3ca5

In ImageClassifierData.from_arrays the attribute .sz is derived from x.shape[1], while PyTorch models need the channel dimension in the 1st axis. This prohibits the use of from_arrays with pretrained models as shown in the minimal nb.

If I am not missing something, I would suggest using [nsamples, channels, x, y] and therefore sz = x.shape[2] in from_arrays and adding documentation.

I would be happy to prepare a pull request, but wanted to make sure first I am not mistaken.",{},{}
17934,IssuesEvent,2018-08-31 15:12:51+00:00,102973646,fastai/fastai,35901082,sgugger,20547620,fastai,closed,CV2 Issue on Mac OSX 10.11.6,[],[],0,"I have performed a 'git pull' today 27-08-2018 and for the fun off it I thought I would run 'pytest tests'. However this fails with an import error for module 'cv2'. I know on mac OS X 10.11.06 there is an issue with `opencsv`  see [http://forums.fast.ai/t/issues-with-import-of-cv2-on-mac-os-x-10-11-6/12920/2](http://forums.fast.ai/t/issues-with-import-of-cv2-on-mac-os-x-10-11-6/12920/2)

My version of 'opencsv' is 3.3.1 which imports without error from python at a terminal. However when I run `pytest tests` I get this error.
> ImportError while importing test module `/Users/mac/FASTAI/fastai/tests/test_core.py`.
> Hint: make sure your test modules/packages have valid Python names.
> Traceback:
> `tests/__init__.py:3`: in <module>
>     import cv2,torch
> E   ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'cv2'

Note there should be 2 underscores either side of the init in tests/init.py but get lost in the posting of this message.

repeated for other test modules

* test_dataset
* test_layer_optimizer
* test_lsuv_initialize
* test_samplers
* test_structured
* test_transform


However the code in `__init__.py` seems to be a fix for ubuntu 16.04. Also `cv2` is only used in 2 modules
* test_lsuv_initializer.py:import cv2 :: which imports it again
* test_transform.py :: which relies on the `__ init __.py` import from 'test_core.py

This also causes and error on import of `torch` if cv2 is removed.

Are the instructions for running the tests correct on the MD page 

The error is still evident after adding testfixtures-6.2.0 to my cpu environment


I finally got the tests to work. Here is what I did

I ran the tests from the `fastai` directory from a terminal. Before I ran the tests I defined the variable `PYTHONPATH` as below

`fastai-cpu) macs-Mac-Pro:fastai mac$ echo $PYTHONPATH
../fastai:/Users/mac/anaconda3/envs/fastai-cpu/lib/python36.zip:/Users/mac/anaconda3/envs/fastai-cpu/lib/python3.6:/Users/mac/anaconda3/envs/fastai-cpu/lib/python3.6/lib-dynload:/Users/mac/anaconda3/envs/fastai-cpu/lib/python3.6/site-packages:/Users/mac/anaconda3/envs/fastai-cpu/lib/python3.6/site-packages/aeosa`

the other thing I did was to rename

`the __init__.py file in tests to my__init__.py`


and used the command

`pytest tests`

 
Things to note 
* As `pytest` runs the tests in `tests` directory it needs the `../fastai` path to find `fastai` module
* Not sure which of the other paths in PYTHONPATH allowed the rest of the collection phase to work.
* Looking at the way modules are imported it seems there is a mismatch with PEP import suggestions

I think this issue can now be closed
",{},{}
