18723,IssuesEvent,2017-11-08 22:15:44+00:00,102692863,onnx/onnx,9300575,bddppq,31675368,onnx,closed,"C++ validation code is desynced from Python code, and tests didn't catch it",[],[],2,"```
bool OpSchema::IsAttributeLegal(const AttributeProto& proto) {
    if (proto.name().empty()) {
        std::cerr << ""Attribute should set name field."" << std::endl;
        return false;
    }   

    int used_fields =
        proto.has_f() +
        proto.has_i() +
        proto.has_s() +
        proto.has_t() +
        proto.has_g() +
        (proto.floats_size() > 0) +
        (proto.ints_size() > 0) +
        (proto.strings_size() > 0) +
        (proto.tensors_size() > 0) +
        (proto.graphs_size() > 0);
    if (used_fields != 1) {
        std::cerr << ""Attribute should contain one and only one value field.\n""
                  << ""AttributeProto:\n""
                  << proto.SerializeAsString()
                  << ""\n""
                  << std::endl;
        return false;
    }   
    return true;
}
```

This is missing test for type consistency.  But more to the point, why do we have both `check_attr` and `is_attribute_legal`.",{},{}
18734,IssuesEvent,2018-08-08 08:39:48+00:00,102692863,onnx/onnx,4865998,JamesAllingham,31675368,onnx,opened,Different initializer formats in ModelProto files,[],[],0,"Hi all,

I've been working on importing ONNX ModelProto files and I've come across something that has confused me. It seems to me that ModelProto files with the same IR version, can store the initializers in different formats.

This is the case with the SqueezeNet found in the old (and deprecated) ONNX [model zoo](https://github.com/lupesko/model-zoo/tree/master/models/image_classification/squeezenet) and the one found in the new [model zoo](https://github.com/onnx/models/tree/master/squeezenet). 

In the case of the older ModelProto, the initializer tensors all seem to be in the *raw_data* field where as in the case of the newer ModelProto, the field containing the initializer tensors seems to be determined by the *data_type* field (i.e. if the datatype is ""Float"" then the corresponding tensor is in the ""float_data"" field).

Is the older format deprecated or must I be able to support both of them? Does the ONNX specification guarantee that if there is data in the raw_data field there will not be any in the other fields? In other words: can I use this to determine which format is being used?",{},{}
